        "text": "Despite ultimately counting for nothing, exit polls create nerve-shredding moments for political leaders and the journalists who commission them.\n\nI’ve been at the sharp end, both as David Cameron’s director of politics and communications in 2015, and the editor of the BBC’s election night coverage in 2010.\n\nThe exit poll ends every election campaign with a bang and — having been uncannily accurate in recent times — is a moment of truth. It clarifies whether dreams have been fulfilled or broken for political parties, while making or destroying reputations among pollsters and journalists.\n\nOn election day, data from around 200 polling stations pours into a secret, featureless room where the numbers are crunched. There are four big dumps of information seen by a small group"
